				\begin{document}$$ {\varDelta}_A=m-A $$\end{document}where ΔA is the mass excess. Since the sum of the mass numbers on either side of a nuclear reaction is the same, A is conserved. If (A + ΔA) is substituted for m in Equation 4, A cancels out because the total number of protons and neutrons between reactants and products are unchanged (charge and mass conservation). We are left with an equation for the Q-value that depends only on the mass excess. For the above example, one can use the mass excess in mass unit (u) to find the Q-value:Q‐value=0.014102+0.016049−0.002603+0.008665×931.5=17.6MeV\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
